<TITLE> European shares rise, oil shares offset rate view </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, July 6 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares rose on Friday as surging crude prices boosted the shares of major oil producers, partially offsetting the impact of US jobs data that dashed expectations for a Federal Reserve rate cut in the next year. The June non-farm payrolls report showed a rise of 132,000 and contained a number of upward revisions for prior monthly data, which painted a more robust picture of the US labor market and limited gains in the stock market. The FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares unofficially ended up 0.6 percent at 1,618.9 points, having retreated from the day's high at 1,618.9 just after the data. Oil stocks were the biggest positive weight on the broader market as crude futures shot above $75 a barrel to their highest level in almost a year. Shares in BP, Total and Royal Dutch Shell were among the top weighted gainers on the FTSEurofirst, as BP rose 1.1 percent and Shell rose 2.6 percent. London's FTSE 100 index rose 0.8 percent, while Frankfurt's DAX gained 0.7 percent and Paris' CAC 40 rose 0.7 perce
